Introduction to Linux

Linux is an open-source operating system based on Unix. Linux is widely used in servers, cloud computing, DevOps environments, and embedded systems.

Linux allows users to interact with the system through a command line interface (CLI) or a graphical user interface (GUI). In DevOps, most work is done using the command line because it is faster and more powerful.

Many popular distributions of Linux exist such as Ubuntu, CentOS, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, and Debian.

Linux is the most commonly used operating system for servers and cloud platforms like Amazon Web Services, Google Cloud, and Microsoft Azure.

Benefits of Linux

Open Source
Linux is free to use and its source code is available to everyone. Developers can modify and customize it according to their needs.

High Security
Linux is considered more secure than many other operating systems because of strong permission systems and frequent updates.

Stability and Performance
Linux systems can run for a long time without restarting. That is why most servers use Linux.

Used in DevOps and Cloud
Most DevOps tools like Docker, Kubernetes, Ansible, and Jenkins run mainly on Linux.

Lightweight
Linux can run even on low hardware systems because it uses fewer resources.

Large Community Support
Linux has a very large community. If any problem occurs, solutions are usually available online.

User Management Commands

Create a new user
sudo adduser username

Example
sudo adduser devops

Delete a user
sudo deluser username

Change password of a user
sudo passwd username

Switch to another user
su username

File Permissions

In Linux every file has permissions for owner, group and others.

To check file permissions
ls -l

Example output
-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu file.txt

Meaning of permissions

r = read
w = write
x = execute

Change File Permission

Command used
chmod permission filename

Example
chmod 777 file.txt

Meaning of numbers

7 = read + write + execute
6 = read + write
5 = read + execute
4 = read

Example for ssh key

chmod 400 key.pem

Change File Ownership

Command
chown user:group filename

Example

sudo chown ubuntu:ubuntu file.txt

Process Management

Process means a running program in the system.

Check running processes
ps

Detailed process list
ps aux

Live monitoring of processes
top

Kill a process
kill processID

Example
kill 1234

Force kill a process
kill -9 1234

Disk Usage Commands

Check disk space
df -h

Check size of folder
du -sh foldername

Example
du -sh /home

Network Commands

Check IP address
ip a

Test internet connection
ping google.com

Check open ports
netstat -tulnp

Package Management (Ubuntu)

Update packages
sudo apt update

Upgrade packages
sudo apt upgrade

Install a package
sudo apt install nginx

Remove a package
sudo apt remove nginx

Search inside files

grep "word" filename

Example
grep "error" logs.txt